properties.Name: Generator
properties.Description:
A device that converts a source of mechanical energy (for example, a diesel or natural gas engine) into electrical energy. 

An electromagnetic device that converts mechanical (rotational) energy into electrical energy. Most large electrical generators are driven by steam or water turbine systems.

Columns.Name: GeneratorId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Generator.

Columns.Name: ManufacturerName
Columns.Description: The name of the party that manufactured the generator.

Columns.Name: ModelNumber
Columns.Description: The generator model number.

Columns.Name: SerialNumber
Columns.Description: The generator serial number.

Columns.Name: CountryOfManufacture
Columns.Description: The country of manufacturer of the generator.

Columns.Name: NormalLifeSpanYears
Columns.Description: The normal life span of the generator expressed in years.

Columns.Name: ScheduledGeneratorIndicator
Columns.Description:
A generating unit which has a nameplate rating of 30 MW or greater or is part of a group of generating units connected at a common connection point with a combined nameplate rating of 30 MW or greater must be classified as a scheduled generating unit unless NEMMCO approves its classification as:
(1) a semi-scheduled generating unit under clause 2.2.7(b); or
(2) a non-scheduled generating unit in accordance with clause 2.2.3(b). Refer to the National Electricity Rules

Columns.Name: SemiScheduledGeneratorIndicator
Columns.Description:
A generating unit which has a nameplate rating of 30 MW or greater or is part of a group of generating units connected at a common connection point with a combined nameplate rated of 30 MW or greater, must be classified as a semi- scheduled generating unit where the output of the generating unit is intermittent unless NEMMCO approves its classification as :
(1) a scheduled generating unit under clause 2.2.2(b); or
(2) a non-scheduled generating unit under clause 2.2.3(b). Refer to the National Electricity Rules.

Columns.Name: BaseLoadGeneratingFacilityIndicator
Columns.Description: Those generating facilities within a utility system that are operated to the greatest extent possible to maximize system mechanical and thermal efficiency and minimize system operating costs.

Columns.Name: IntermittentGeneratorIndicator
Columns.Description: A description of a generating unit whose output is not readily predictable, including, without limitation, solar generators, wave turbine generators, wind turbine generators and hydro-generators without any material storage capability

Columns.Name: AlternatingGeneratorIndicator
Columns.Description: An electric generator for producing alternating current.

Columns.Name: AsynchronousGeneratingUnitIndicator
Columns.Description: Generators that are not synchronized to the system frequency, typically wind turbines and Photovoltaic cells

Columns.Name: PeakingGeneratorIndicator
Columns.Description: A generating system designed to run almost constantly at near maximum capacity levels, usually at lower cost than intermediate or peaking generating systems.

Columns.Name: BackStartCapabilityIndicator
Columns.Description:
In relation to a generating unit, the ability to start and synchronize without using supply from the power system. 

A capability that allows a generating unit, following its disconnection from the power system, to be able to deliver electricity to either: (a) its connection point; or (b) a suitable point in the network from which supply can be made available to other generating units, without taking supply from any part of the power system following disconnection.

Columns.Name: EmbeddedGeneratorIndicator
Columns.Description:
A generator connected to the distribution network, or connected to a distribution network customer.  (Not a transmission connected generator).

National Electricity Rules Definition :
A generator connected within a distribution network and not having direct access to the transmission network.

Columns.Name: ExemptedGeneratorIndicator
Columns.Description: A generator exempted from the registration process, typically below 5MW and non-market.

Columns.Name: NonScheduledGeneratorIndicator
Columns.Description:
A generator that: 

sells energy into the energy spot market, and 
is not scheduled by AERO as part of central dispatch, and 
has been classified as an MNS generating unit in accordance with Chapter 2 of the NER.

Columns.Name: MarketScheduledGeneratorIndicator
Columns.Description:
A generator that: 

sells energy into the energy spot market
is scheduled by AERO as part of central dispatch, and 
has been classified as an MS generating unit in accordance with Chapter 2 of the NER.

Columns.Name: NonMarketScheduledGeneratorNmsIndicator
Columns.Description:
A generator that: 

sells its entire output directly to a local retailer or customer at the same connection point under a power purchase agreement (not through the spot market), and 
is scheduled by AERO as part of central dispatch, and 
has been classified as an NMS generating unit in accordance with Chapter 2 of the NER.

Columns.Name: TimeToFireupFromColdStateMinutes
Columns.Description:
Gas and Coal-fired Boilers   8-48 hours
Gas Turbine   20 minutes
Water (Hydro)   1 minute
Renewable (Wind/Solar)   dependent on prevailing weather

Columns.Name: CompanyOwnedIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates whether the generator is owned by the company or an external party.

Columns.Name: GeneratorTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Generator Type.

Columns.Name: GeneratingStationId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Generating Station.

Columns.Name: GeneratorCoolingMethodTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Generator Cooling Method.

Columns.Name: TurbineId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Turbine.

Columns.Name: DamId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Dam.

Columns.Name: FuelTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a fuel type.

Columns.Name: AsperationTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of an asperation type.

Columns.Name: GeneratorCoolingSystemTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Generator Cooling System Type.

Columns.Name: UninterruptablePowerSupplyIndicator
Columns.Description:
Indicates that the generator has an uninterruptable power supply.

A system designed to provide power without delay or transients during any period that the normal power supply is incapable of performing acceptably. To avoid a brief (10-20 second) interruption of power, a UPS can be used on critical equipment to provide continuous power during the seconds between a utility outage and the restoration of back-up power provided by a standby generator.

Columns.Name: AutomaticTransferSwitchIndicator
Columns.Description:
Indicates that the generator has an automatic transfer switch.

A mechanical device that switches an electrical load from a preferred source, usually a utility service, to an alternate source, usually an emergency generator. It also incorporates controls to start and stop the generator and timer functions to coordinate the transfer.

Columns.Name: AutomaticControlPanelIndicator
Columns.Description: A unit that starts the genset in case of mains failure, main circuit breaker, differential protection and all auxiliary controls and alarms.

Columns.Name: AutomaticVoltageRegulatorIndicator
Columns.Description: An electronic device designed to increase accuracy on output voltage of alternators.

Columns.Name: GeneratorFuelTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a generator fuel type.

Columns.Name: GeneratorPowerPhaseTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a generator power phase type.

Columns.Name: GeneratorEnclosureTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a generator enclosure type.

Properties.Description:
A device that converts a source of mechanical energy (for example, a diesel or natural gas engine) into electrical energy. 

An electromagnetic device that converts mechanical (rotational) energy into electrical energy. Most large electrical generators are driven by steam or water turbine systems.
